<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>Who had the MOST direct influence on American business development in the early 1900s?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Henry Ford through assembly line production</option>
            <option letter="b">J.P. Morgan through financial consolidation</option>
            <option letter="c">William Randolph Hearst through newspaper empire</option>
            <option letter="d">Andrew Carnegie through philanthropic giving</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>Henry Ford's development of the assembly line and $5 workday revolutionized not just auto manufacturing but American industry as a whole. His methods became the model for mass production across industries, raised wages nationwide, created the modern consumer economy, and transformed transportation. While Morgan controlled more wealth, Hearst influenced public opinion, and Carnegie funded institutions, Ford's innovations most directly changed how American business operated.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
